  "issue_number": 26,
  "issue_title": "Startup health hook hangs forever after application `main()` crashes before binding the server",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\nIf the application `main()` throws before the HTTP server starts, `jvm-live-reload` logs the exception in the app thread but the request that triggered startup never receives an error.\n\n`HealthCheckStartupHook` keeps polling `/health` forever, even though the app thread is already dead and the target port will never become healthy.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. Publish local artifacts:\n```sh\nexport JDK_JAVA_OPTIONS=\"--add-opens=java.base/java.util=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED\"\n./gradlew publishToMavenLocal\n```\n\n2. Create a temporary Gradle app using the plugin with:\n```kotlin\nliveReload {\n    settings = mapOf(\n        \"live.reload.http.port\" to \"18180\",\n        \"live.reload.proxy.http.port\" to \"19180\",\n        \"live.reload.debug\" to \"true\"\n    )\n}\n```\n\n3. Use an app that crashes before opening the target server:\n```java\npublic class App {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\"APP_MAIN_ABOUT_TO_CRASH\");\n    throw new RuntimeException(\"boom before binding HTTP server\");\n  }\n}\n```\n\n4. Start:\n```sh\n./gradlew liveReloadRun --info --continuous\n```\n\n5. Trigger first startup through the proxy:\n```sh\ncurl --max-time 5 -i http://localhost:19180/anything\n```\n\n## Actual Result\nThe app crash is logged:\n```text\n\ud83d\udd03 Reloading an application\n\ud83d\ude80 Starting App\nAPP_MAIN_ABOUT_TO_CRASH\nError in application main thread\nCaused by: java.lang.RuntimeException: boom before binding HTTP server\n```\n\nBut the client receives no response and times out:\n```text\ncurl: (28) Operation timed out after 5004 milliseconds with 0 bytes received\n```\n\nThe proxy remains listening while the target app never bound its port:\n```text\nLISTEN 127.0.0.1:19180 users:((\"java\",pid=2799074,...))\n```\n\n## Expected Result\nWhen the application main thread dies during startup, the startup hook should abort and the proxy should return a clear HTTP error instead of hanging indefinitely.\n\n## Evidence\n`BaseDevServerStart.startInternal()` starts the app thread, logs `InvocationTargetException`, but does not propagate failure to the startup hook:\n```java\nappThread.start();\nrunHooks(appThread, classLoader, startupHooks);\n```\n\n`HealthCheckStartupHook` loops forever on connection failure:\n```java\nwhile (true) {\n  var healthResponse = isHealthy(...);\n  if (healthResponse == 1) return;\n  else if (healthResponse == 0) Thread.sleep(50L);\n  else if (healthResponse == -1) Thread.sleep(50L);\n}\n```\n\n## Root Cause\nStartup readiness polling only observes the health endpoint. It does not observe application thread liveness or capture exceptions thrown by `main()`.\n\n## Security/Business Impact\nA simple startup bug can wedge the dev proxy indefinitely. Developers get hanging HTTP requests instead of actionable feedback, and must kill the build JVM to recover.\n\n## Suggested Fix\nTrack app thread startup failure and stop polling when the app thread exits before health succeeds.\n\nPossible remediation:\n```java\nif (!th.isAlive()) {\n  throw new UnrecoverableException(\"Application exited before health check became ready\");\n}\n```\n\nAdd this check inside `HealthCheckStartupHook` and `GrpcHealthCheckStartupHook`, and preserve/log the original exception from the app thread where possible.",
